  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison tells Oliver Johnson to use his own judgement regarding articles sent to the Independent. Garrison read Oliver Johnson&apos;s account of a trip to New Hampshire with great interest. Garrison has not yet relinquished the idea of writing a history of the anti-slavery cause. He doubts if Edmund Quincy would undertake the task, but Garrison would be glad to join Oliver Johnson and others in asking him. Garrison approves of the Independent&apos;s refusal to take notice of &quot;the clerical orthodox bull issued against it in Chicago.&quot;</subfield>
